HEADWORD: Epizoötic
<hw>Ep`i*zo*⟦oum⟧t"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧pizo⟦oum⟧tique</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Zo⟦oum⟧l.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to an
epizo⟦oum⟧n.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>Containing fossil remains; --
said of rocks, formations, mountains, and the like.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Epizo⟦oum⟧tic</qex> mountains are of secondary formation.</q>
<rj><qau>Kirwan.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of the nature of a disease which attacks many
animals at the same time; -- corresponding to epidemic diseases among
men.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Epizootic</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Epizooty</ent>⟦br⟧
